      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Discussion: In her landmark The Death and Life of Great American Cities1, Jane Jacobs described the dangers of gentrification, but she also made an important point. The problem is not when the wealth of a neighborhood increases from poverty to a mix of incomes — a condition she called “unslumming”. The problem arises when the neighborhood tips over from there into higher income, driving out those of more moderate income. She called this “the self-destruction of diversity.” In other words, increasing wealth that increases diversity is good, but increasing wealth that decreases diversity is very bad — perhaps as bad as decreasing wealth that also decreases diversity (e.g. when a neighborhood declines into a slum).",
      "id": "84892002971382"
    },
